Bank Churn Prediction

Problem Statement

Context

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customers location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values

** 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) ** 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# Function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    Parameters:
    data: dataframe - The input dataset
    predictor: str - Name of the independent variable column
    target: str - Name of the target variable column
    """
    # Get the number of unique categories in the predictor
    count = data[predictor].nunique()

    # Determine the category to sort by (least frequent category in the target variable)
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]

    # Create a cross-tabulation of predictor and target, including row totals
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)  # Print a separator line

    # Create a normalized cross-tabulation (proportions instead of counts)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )

    # Plot the stacked bar chart
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))

    # Configure the legend
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))

    # Display the plot
    plt.show()

Data Normalization

We normalize numerical features to ensure all variables are on the same scale. This prevents features with larger magnitudes from dominating the model's learning process. Using StandardScaler, we transform each feature to have a mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1, which improves model performance and stability.

In[634]:
# List of numerical columns to be normalized
cols_list = ['CreditScore', 'Age', 'Tenure', 'Balance', 'NumOfProducts', 'EstimatedSalary']

# Creating an instance of the standard scaler
sc = StandardScaler()

# Fit and transform the training data
X_train[cols_list] = sc.fit_transform(X_train[cols_list])

# Transform the validation data

Model Evaluation Criterion

I'll primarily use recall as my main evaluation metric. Recall is crucial because it measures my model's ability to identify customers likely to churn, which is vital for the bank's retention efforts. I'll also consider accuracy, precision, and F1 score as secondary metrics to provide a comprehensive view of model performance.

In[635]:
def make_confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    actual_targets: actual target (dependent) variable values
    predicted_targets: predicted target (dependent) variable values
    """
    # Create the confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets)

    # Create labels for each cell in the confusion matrix
    # Each label will show the count and percentage of total
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(cm.shape[0], cm.shape[1])

    # Create a new figure with specified size
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    # Plot the heatmap of the confusion matrix
    # 'annot' adds the labels to each cell, 'fmt' ensures no additional formatting
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")

    # Set the y-axis label
    plt.ylabel("True label")

    # Set the x-axis label
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Neural Network with SGD Optimizer Performance

Loss Plot Observations

  • The model shows a steady decrease in loss for both training and validation sets over 100 epochs.
  • Training and validation loss curves are closely aligned, suggesting good generalization.
  • Final loss values are around 0.40-0.41, indicating room for improvement.
  • No signs of overfitting, as validation loss doesn't increase relative to training loss.

Recall Plot Observations

  • Recall starts very low (near 0) for both sets and improves slowly over time.
  • There's high volatility in recall values, especially in early epochs.
  • Recall improves more consistently after about 40 epochs.
  • Final recall values reach approximately 0.22-0.24, which is quite low for a binary classification task.
  • Validation recall slightly outperforms training recall in later epochs, which is unusual.

Overall Assessment

  • The model is learning, but performance is suboptimal, especially in terms of recall.
  • Low recall suggests the model struggles to identify positive cases (customers who will churn).
  • The slow, steady improvement indicates SGD might be using a low learning rate.

Neural Network with Adam Optimizer Performance

Loss Plot Observations

  • Both training and validation loss decrease rapidly in the first 20 epochs.
  • The loss curves converge and stabilize around epoch 40.
  • Final loss values are approximately 0.34, lower than the SGD model.
  • Validation loss closely follows training loss, indicating good generalization.

Recall Plot Observations

  • Recall improves dramatically in the first 20 epochs for both sets.
  • Validation recall consistently outperforms training recall.
  • Recall stabilizes around epoch 60, with validation recall at ~0.5 and training recall at ~0.45.
  • The model shows significant improvement over the SGD optimizer in terms of recall.

Classification Report Analysis (Validation Set)

  • Overall accuracy: 86% (0.86)
  • Class 0 (non-churn):
    • High precision (0.88) and recall (0.96)
    • Excellent F1-score (0.92)
  • Class 1 (churn):
    • Good precision (0.74)
    • Moderate recall (0.48)
    • F1-score of 0.58, indicating room for improvement in churn prediction
  • Macro average F1-score: 0.75
  • Weighted average F1-score: 0.85

Overall Assessment

  • The Adam optimizer significantly outperforms the SGD optimizer.
  • The model shows good overall performance, especially for identifying non-churning customers.
  • There's a class imbalance, with more non-churn than churn cases.
  • Churn prediction (Class 1) needs improvement, particularly in recall.
  • The model generalizes well, with validation metrics often exceeding training metrics.

Neural Network with Adam Optimizer and Dropout Performance

Loss Plot Observations

  • Rapid decrease in loss for both training and validation sets in the first 10 epochs.
  • Loss stabilizes around epoch 20, with slight fluctuations afterwards.
  • Final loss values are approximately 0.33 for training and 0.35 for validation.
  • Validation loss is slightly higher than training loss, indicating good regularization effect from dropout.

Recall Plot Observations

  • Sharp increase in recall for both sets in the first 10 epochs.
  • Validation recall consistently outperforms training recall until later epochs.
  • Both recalls stabilize around 0.5 after 60 epochs, with high volatility.
  • Final recall values fluctuate between 0.45 and 0.5 for both sets.

Classification Report Analysis (Validation Set)

  • Overall accuracy: 87% (0.87), slightly improved from the previous model.
  • Class 0 (non-churn):
    • High precision (0.88) and excellent recall (0.97)
    • Strong F1-score (0.92)
  • Class 1 (churn):
    • Improved precision (0.78) compared to the previous model
    • Recall remains moderate (0.48)
    • Slightly improved F1-score (0.59)
  • Macro average F1-score: 0.76
  • Weighted average F1-score: 0.85

Overall Assessment

  • The addition of dropout has slightly improved the model's performance.
  • Better generalization is evident from the closer alignment of training and validation metrics.
  • The model excels at identifying non-churning customers (Class 0).
  • Churn prediction (Class 1) shows improved precision but recall remains a challenge.
  • High volatility in recall suggests the model might benefit from a larger batch size or learning rate adjustments.

Comparison to Previous Model

  • Slight improvement in overall accuracy (87% vs 86%).
  • Improved precision for churn prediction (0.78 vs 0.74).
  • Recall for churn prediction remains the same (0.48).
  • Loss curves show more regularization effect, potentially reducing overfitting.

Neural Network with Balanced Data (SMOTE) and SGD Optimizer Performance

Loss Plot Observations

  • Both training and validation loss decrease steadily over 100 epochs.
  • Training loss decreases more rapidly than validation loss after epoch 20.
  • Final loss values: training ~0.45, validation ~0.48.
  • The gap between training and validation loss suggests some overfitting.

Recall Plot Observations

  • Dramatic improvement in recall for both sets over 100 epochs.
  • Training recall outperforms validation recall after epoch 30.
  • Final recall values: training ~0.80, validation ~0.77.
  • The model shows significant improvement in recall compared to previous models.

Classification Report Analysis (Validation Set)

  • Overall accuracy: 76% (0.76), lower than previous models.
  • Class 0 (non-churn):
    • High precision (0.93) but lower recall (0.76)
    • Good F1-score (0.83)
  • Class 1 (churn):
    • Low precision (0.45) but high recall (0.77)
    • Improved F1-score (0.57) for churn prediction
  • Macro average F1-score: 0.70
  • Weighted average F1-score: 0.78

Overall Assessment

  • SMOTE balancing has significantly improved recall for churning customers.
  • The model now shows a more balanced performance between classes.
  • There's a trade-off: improved churn detection at the cost of more false positives.
  • Overfitting is evident from the diverging loss curves and recall performance.

Comparison to Previous Models

  • Highest recall for churn prediction (0.77) among all models.
  • Lower overall accuracy due to increased false positives.
  • More balanced performance between classes, addressing the class imbalance issue.

# Define a custom scoring function using ROC AUC
def custom_scorer(model, X, y):
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    return roc_auc_score(y, y_pred)

# Implement permutation importance for Keras models
def permutation_importance_keras(model, X, y, n_repeats=10, random_state=0):
    np.random.seed(random_state)
    baseline_score = custom_scorer(model, X, y)
    importances = []

    # Iterate over each feature
    for column in X.columns:
        scores = []
        for _ in range(n_repeats):
            # Create a copy with the current feature permuted
            X_permuted = X.copy()
            X_permuted[column] = np.random.permutation(X_permuted[column])

            # Calculate importance as decrease in performance
            score = custom_scorer(model, X_permuted, y)
            scores.append(baseline_score - score)

        # Store mean importance for the feature
        importances.append(np.mean(scores))

    return np.array(importances)

def plot_feature_importance(importance, names, model_type):
    # Create arrays from feature importance and feature names
    feature_importance = np.array(importance)
    feature_names = np.array(names)

    # Create a DataFrame using a Dictionary
    data = {'feature_names': feature_names, 'feature_importance': feature_importance}
    fi_df = pd.DataFrame(data)

    # Sort the DataFrame in order decreasing feature importance
    fi_df.sort_values(by=['feature_importance'], ascending=False, inplace=True)

    # Define size of bar plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    # Plot Seaborn bar chart
    sns.barplot(x=fi_df['feature_importance'], y=fi_df['feature_names'])
    # Add chart labels
    plt.title(model_type + ' FEATURE IMPORTANCE')
    plt.xlabel('FEATURE IMPORTANCE')
    plt.ylabel('FEATURE NAMES')

# Assuming X_test and y_test are your test data
importances = permutation_importance_keras(model_3, X_test, y_test, n_repeats=10, random_state=42)

# Get feature names (assuming X_test is a DataFrame)
feature_names = X_test.columns.tolist()

# Plot feature importances
plot_feature_importance(importances, feature_names, 'Neural Network (Model 3)')

# Print feature importances
for i, feature in enumerate(feature_names):
    print(f"{feature}: {importances[i]:.4f}")

Why "NN with SMOTE, Adam & Dropout" is the Best Model for Bank Churn Prediction

Performance Metrics

  • Validation Recall: 0.794944 (highest among all models)
  • Training Recall: 0.784450 (third highest, but very close to the best)

Handling Imbalanced Data

  • Incorporates SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique)
  • Successfully addresses the class imbalance issue in the dataset
  • Critical for accurately predicting the minority class (churned customers)

Optimization and Regularization

  • Uses Adam optimizer
    • Adaptive learning rate for faster convergence
    • Often performs well on large datasets
  • Implements Dropout
    • Reduces overfitting by randomly deactivating neurons during training
    • Improves model generalization

Generalization

  • Small difference between training (0.784450) and validation (0.794944) recall
  • Indicates excellent generalization to unseen data
  • Slight improvement on validation set suggests robust learning without overfitting

Business Relevance

  • High recall is crucial for churn prediction
    • Identifies approximately 79.5% of potential churners
    • Allows for highly effective proactive retention strategies

Model Stability

  • Combination of SMOTE, Adam, and Dropout provides a balanced approach
    • SMOTE addresses data imbalance
    • Adam offers efficient optimization
    • Dropout prevents overfitting

Overall Effectiveness

  • Outperforms other architectures, including:
    • Basic neural networks
    • Models without dropout
    • Models using different optimizers (e.g., SGD)
  • Achieves the best balance of high performance and generalization

Conclusion

The "NN with SMOTE, Adam & Dropout" model provides the optimal combination of performance, generalization, and robustness for the bank churn prediction task. Its high recall on both training and validation sets, coupled with its ability to handle imbalanced data and prevent overfitting, makes it the best choice for deployment in a real-world banking environment.
